From cou.: 0 Journal
From Soup: 0 Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 Metal catalyzed asymmetric oxidation of prochiral sulfides is one of the prevailing strategies to produce enantiopure sulfoxides. Keeping in view the reported reactivity of peroxo vanadium complexes towards asymmetric oxidation reactions, this study explores the reactivity of vanadia represented as a VO4 cluster with CH3-S-Ph through DFT computations. The mechanism of the oxidation of sulfides to sulfoxides with unsupported VO4 is thoroughly investigated. The chiral centre in the VO4 cluster is introduced by grafting it on an SBA-15 support and two conformers of the supported cluster are thus obtained. The study was extended to locate transition states for the reaction of each conformer with CH3-S-Ph. The large enantiomeric excess obtained from the energy difference of the transition states confirms the formation of enantiopure sulfoxide. Analysis of the computational results provides a rational explanation for the observed enantioselectivity, which is remarkable. The optical stability as well as asymmetry of chiral sulfoxides obtained by the current approach has been further confirmed by locating the planar transition state, through which conversion from one enantiomer to another takes place. The calculations suggest that transition between the two enantiomers of sulfoxide is hampered by sufficiently high inversion barriers.
From Soup: 1 Metal catalyzed asymmetric oxidation of prochiral sulfides is one of the prevailing strategies to produce enantiopure sulfoxides. Keeping in view the reported reactivity of peroxo vanadium complexes towards asymmetric oxidation reactions, this study explores the reactivity of vanadia represented as a VO 4 cluster with CH 3 -S-Ph through DFT computations. The mechanism of the oxidation of sulfides to sulfoxides with unsupported VO 4 is thoroughly investigated. The chiral centre in the VO 4 cluster is introduced by grafting it on an SBA-15 support and two conformers of the supported cluster are thus obtained. The study was extended to locate transition states for the reaction of each conformer with CH 3 -S-Ph. The large enantiomeric excess obtained from the energy difference of the transition states confirms the formation of enantiopure sulfoxide. Analysis of the computational results provides a rational explanation for the observed enantioselectivity, which is remarkable. The optical stability as well as asymmetry of chiral sulfoxides obtained by the current approach has been further confirmed by locating the planar transition state, through which conversion from one enantiomer to another takes place. The calculations suggest that transition between the two enantiomers of sulfoxide is hampered by sufficiently high inversion barriers.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 The growth in the chemistry of organic sulfoxides during the last decade has been due to their importance as synthetic intermediates for the production of a broad range of chemically and biologically active molecules. The vast chemistry of sulfoxides makes them valuable reagents in organic synthesis.1–3 The high optical stability and symmetry of chiral sulfoxides boosts their applications, and they have been extensively employed as chiral auxiliaries and ligands in a series of organic asymmetric syntheses.1,4 Numerous synthetic approaches using chemical,5–8 microbiological9–11 or enzymatic12–17 methods are reported in the literature to obtain chiral sulfoxides. Chemical methods include two general techniques i.e. nucleophilic substitution of optically active sulfur derivatives5,18 and asymmetric oxidation of prochiral sulfides, i.e. chiral sulfoxidation.19 The prevailing approach for the preparation of enantiopure sulfoxide is metal catalyzed asymmetric oxidation of sulfides. Kagan20 and Modena21 introduced titanium complexes into this reaction system. Later, metallo-schiff base complexes, with a variety of metal centers like vanadium, manganese, or iron, with a range of ligands such as diols, triols, Schiff bases and double Schiff bases, amino acids and amino alcohols were also employed.22–25 Among other transition metals, a vanadium based catalyst obtained by the combination of Schiff bases derived from chiral amino alcohols and [VO(acac)2], using aqueous hydrogen peroxide as an oxidant reported by Bolm and Bienewald has been widely studied.26 Biologically, chiral sulfoxidations are carried out by enzymes in plants or microorganisms, particularly by peroxidases. Among them, vanadium-dependent haloperoxidases (VHPO) are an important class of enzymes that possess this function.27 Vanadium based systems have been developed as models for VHPO for instance vanadium-Schiff bases, vanadium-amino acids, and vanadium-amino alcohols.28–30 Various computational studies on oxidation catalyzed by vanadium complexes considering biomimetic models of haloperoxidases are available in the literature.31–33
From Soup: 2 The growth in the chemistry of organic sulfoxides during the last decade has been due to their importance as synthetic intermediates for the production of a broad range of chemically and biologically active molecules. The vast chemistry of sulfoxides makes them valuable reagents in organic synthesis. 1–3 The high optical stability and symmetry of chiral sulfoxides boosts their applications, and they have been extensively employed as chiral auxiliaries and ligands in a series of organic asymmetric syntheses. 1,4 Numerous synthetic approaches using chemical, 5–8 microbiological 9–11 or enzymatic 12–17 methods are reported in the literature to obtain chiral sulfoxides. Chemical methods include two general techniques i.e. nucleophilic substitution of optically active sulfur derivatives 5,18 and asymmetric oxidation of prochiral sulfides, i.e. chiral sulfoxidation. 19 The prevailing approach for the preparation of enantiopure sulfoxide is metal catalyzed asymmetric oxidation of sulfides. Kagan 20 and Modena 21 introduced titanium complexes into this reaction system. Later, metallo-schiff base complexes, with a variety of metal centers like vanadium, manganese, or iron, with a range of ligands such as diols, triols, Schiff bases and double Schiff bases, amino acids and amino alcohols were also employed. 22–25 Among other transition metals, a vanadium based catalyst obtained by the combination of Schiff bases derived from chiral amino alcohols and [VO(acac) 2 ], using aqueous hydrogen peroxide as an oxidant reported by Bolm and Bienewald has been widely studied. 26 Biologically, chiral sulfoxidations are carried out by enzymes in plants or microorganisms, particularly by peroxidases. Among them, vanadium-dependent haloperoxidases (VHPO) are an important class of enzymes that possess this function. 27 Vanadium based systems have been developed as models for VHPO for instance vanadium-Schiff bases, vanadium-amino acids, and vanadium-amino alcohols. 28–30 Various computational studies on oxidation catalyzed by vanadium complexes considering biomimetic models of haloperoxidases are available in the literature. 31–33
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 A large number of vanadium based catalysts have been reported for asymmetric synthesis of chiral sulfoxides.28–36 Vanadium oxide clusters are well established catalysts for various organic reactions due to their ability to adopt various oxidation states, stoichiometries, and coordination modes. A recent experimental study by Huang et al.37 has reported a V8 cluster based homogeneous catalyst for asymmetric sulfoxidation reactions in water in the presence of serium albumin with moderate enantioselectivity. Among the various vanadium oxide clusters, VO4 belongs to a peroxo complex,38,39 and the presence of a peroxo linkage mimics its structure to the VHPO models. The catalytic behavior of vanadium oxide can be improved by depositing it on an appropriate support;40–42 SBA-15 is reportedly a promising support material for catalysts.43,44 Various experimental studies report the promising reactivity of transition metal oxides supported on mesoporous supports such as SBA-15 and MCM-41 towards enantioselective oxidation.45,46 The details of the experimental procedure to synthesize SBA-15 are reported in the literature45 and it has been verified by density functional calculations that a bicyclic cluster model is the most suitable cluster model to mimic the geometry of silica rings in a SBA-15 mesoporous molecular sieve.47 Exciting progress has been made in mechanistic understanding of chemical reactions, stereochemistry, and catalysis through computational chemistry. The rigorous computations made possible by incredible progress in the speed of computers and advances in theory provide reliable understanding of the mechanistic pathways and transition structures encountered in the reaction. The hybrid QM/MM method allows quantum mechanical (QM) treatment of large systems wherein the chemically important region is treated by an accurate QM method and the remaining region is approximated by efficient but low-level molecular mechanics (MM) methods.
From Soup: 3 A large number of vanadium based catalysts have been reported for asymmetric synthesis of chiral sulfoxides. 28–36 Vanadium oxide clusters are well established catalysts for various organic reactions due to their ability to adopt various oxidation states, stoichiometries, and coordination modes. A recent experimental study by Huang et al. 37 has reported a V 8 cluster based homogeneous catalyst for asymmetric sulfoxidation reactions in water in the presence of serium albumin with moderate enantioselectivity. Among the various vanadium oxide clusters, VO 4 belongs to a peroxo complex, 38,39 and the presence of a peroxo linkage mimics its structure to the VHPO models. The catalytic behavior of vanadium oxide can be improved by depositing it on an appropriate support; 40–42 SBA-15 is reportedly a promising support material for catalysts. 43,44 Various experimental studies report the promising reactivity of transition metal oxides supported on mesoporous supports such as SBA-15 and MCM-41 towards enantioselective oxidation. 45,46 The details of the experimental procedure to synthesize SBA-15 are reported in the literature 45 and it has been verified by density functional calculations that a bicyclic cluster model is the most suitable cluster model to mimic the geometry of silica rings in a SBA-15 mesoporous molecular sieve. 47 Exciting progress has been made in mechanistic understanding of chemical reactions, stereochemistry, and catalysis through computational chemistry. The rigorous computations made possible by incredible progress in the speed of computers and advances in theory provide reliable understanding of the mechanistic pathways and transition structures encountered in the reaction. The hybrid QM/MM method allows quantum mechanical (QM) treatment of large systems wherein the chemically important region is treated by an accurate QM method and the remaining region is approximated by efficient but low-level molecular mechanics (MM) methods.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 In this work, we present a computational study performed within the formalism of density functional theory (DFT) on the origin of enantioselectivity in the oxidation of prochiral sulfide (CH3-S-Ph) to sulfoxide using a VO4 cluster grafted on a SBA-15 support. The heterogenization of the cluster on the support offers a novel approach towards the synthesis of enantiopure sulfoxide as it generates a stereocentre in the metal oxide cluster. A chiral catalyst is known to promote the preferential reactivity of one of the enantioselective pathways that selectively leads to the formation of the product at the end of the reaction.48,49 Instead of employing an unrealistic simplified model, the reactivity of both the experimentally viable conformers of the supported cluster with CH3-S-Ph is investigated using the QM/MM approach to decipher the mechanism of asymmetric synthesis of sulfoxide. The detailed analysis of electronic and steric effects offers conclusive evidence of high enantioselectivity in the reaction.
From Soup: 4 In this work, we present a computational study performed within the formalism of density functional theory (DFT) on the origin of enantioselectivity in the oxidation of prochiral sulfide (CH 3 -S-Ph) to sulfoxide using a VO 4 cluster grafted on a SBA-15 support. The heterogenization of the cluster on the support offers a novel approach towards the synthesis of enantiopure sulfoxide as it generates a stereocentre in the metal oxide cluster. A chiral catalyst is known to promote the preferential reactivity of one of the enantioselective pathways that selectively leads to the formation of the product at the end of the reaction. 48,49 Instead of employing an unrealistic simplified model, the reactivity of both the experimentally viable conformers of the supported cluster with CH 3 -S-Ph is investigated using the QM/MM approach to decipher the mechanism of asymmetric synthesis of sulfoxide. The detailed analysis of electronic and steric effects offers conclusive evidence of high enantioselectivity in the reaction.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 All calculations reported in the study have been performed by employing the hybrid B3LYP exchange correlation functional50 in combination with the all electron polarized triple ζ valence basis set (TZVP) augmented by a set of polarization functions (a p-set for vanadium, a d-set for oxygen)51 for quantum mechanical (QM) calculations. The accuracy and reliability of the employed level of theory has already been established in our previous work that reports direct hydroxylation of benzene with the aid of a V4O10 cluster.52 All gas phase geometries and transition states were optimized using the B3LYP functional with empirical dispersion added to it (B3LYP-D3).53 This functional contains both exact exchange and dispersion corrections that play important roles in correctly describing weak interactions. The molecular mechanics (MM) calculations were carried out using the universal force field (UFF).54 The QM/MM calculations have been performed using the ONIOM55 model as implemented in the Gaussian 09 (D.01 revision) suite of programs.56 Various possible modes of interaction for the reaction between VO4 and CH3-S-Ph have been explored by performing relaxed potential energy surface (PES) scans along different reaction coordinates such as dihedral angle and bond lengths. The transition states (TS) were located using the TS Berny algorithm method.57 In addition to optimization, vibrational analyses have been performed for all the geometries to confirm that the intermediates correspond to stable points on the PES and the TSs correspond to a first order saddle point. The connectivity of the TSs with the local minima was established by performing intrinsic reaction coordinate (IRC) calculations.58 Atomic charges and atomic spin densities were analyzed by natural bond order (NBO 6.0).59 The change in Gibbs free energy (ΔG) for the reaction of VO4 with CH3-S-Ph was calculated according to the equation below:
From Soup: 5 All calculations reported in the study have been performed by employing the hybrid B3LYP exchange correlation functional 50 in combination with the all electron polarized triple ζ valence basis set (TZVP) augmented by a set of polarization functions (a p-set for vanadium, a d-set for oxygen) 51 for quantum mechanical (QM) calculations. The accuracy and reliability of the employed level of theory has already been established in our previous work that reports direct hydroxylation of benzene with the aid of a V 4 O 10 cluster. 52 All gas phase geometries and transition states were optimized using the B3LYP functional with empirical dispersion added to it (B3LYP-D3). 53 This functional contains both exact exchange and dispersion corrections that play important roles in correctly describing weak interactions. The molecular mechanics (MM) calculations were carried out using the universal force field (UFF). 54 The QM/MM calculations have been performed using the ONIOM 55 model as implemented in the Gaussian 09 (D.01 revision) suite of programs. 56 Various possible modes of interaction for the reaction between VO 4 and CH 3 -S-Ph have been explored by performing relaxed potential energy surface (PES) scans along different reaction coordinates such as dihedral angle and bond lengths. The transition states (TS) were located using the TS Berny algorithm method. 57 In addition to optimization, vibrational analyses have been performed for all the geometries to confirm that the intermediates correspond to stable points on the PES and the TSs correspond to a first order saddle point. The connectivity of the TSs with the local minima was established by performing intrinsic reaction coordinate (IRC) calculations. 58 Atomic charges and atomic spin densities were analyzed by natural bond order (NBO 6.0). 59 The change in Gibbs free energy (Δ G ) for the reaction of VO 4 with CH 3 -S-Ph was calculated according to the equation below:
