From cou.: 7 To explore the reactivity of a VO4 moiety towards methyl phenyl sulfide, the structures of both the reactants (VO4 moiety and CH3-S-Ph) were optimized; the VO4 moiety contains two oxo oxygens (O2−) (labeled as O1 and O2) bonded to vanadium and a peroxide linkage (O22−) (labeled as O3 and O4) as shown in Fig. 2(a). The optimized structure of VO4 corresponds to the formula V(O)2(O2) and it is a peroxo complex. The peroxo structure of VO4 is reported in the literature by Jakubikove et al.39 and Sauer and Vyboishchikov.38 Formally, VO4 can be formed from V6+, two O2− and one O22− with V6+ being an open shell species with 5 electrons in valence p orbitals ([Ne] 3s2 3p5). The VO4 belongs to an open shell system (with one unpaired electron) with ground state spin multiplicity as a doublet. The C–H and C–S bond lengths in the optimized structure of methyl phenyl sulfide are 1.09 Å and 1.80 Å respectively (Fig. 2(b)).
From Soup: 7 To explore the reactivity of a VO 4 moiety towards methyl phenyl sulfide, the structures of both the reactants (VO 4 moiety and CH 3 -S-Ph) were optimized; the VO 4 moiety contains two oxo oxygens (O 2− ) (labeled as O 1 and O 2 ) bonded to vanadium and a peroxide linkage (O 2 2− ) (labeled as O 3 and O 4 ) as shown in Fig. 2(a) . The optimized structure of VO 4 corresponds to the formula V(O) 2 (O 2 ) and it is a peroxo complex. The peroxo structure of VO 4 is reported in the literature by Jakubikove et al. 39 and Sauer and Vyboishchikov. 38 Formally, VO 4 can be formed from V 6+ , two O 2− and one O 2 2− with V 6+ being an open shell species with 5 electrons in valence p orbitals ([Ne] 3s 2 3p 5 ). The VO 4 belongs to an open shell system (with one unpaired electron) with ground state spin multiplicity as a doublet. The C–H and C–S bond lengths in the optimized structure of methyl phenyl sulfide are 1.09 Å and 1.80 Å respectively ( Fig. 2(b) ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 The VO4 moiety has a high electron affinity of 81.71 kcal mol−1 (the adiabatic electron affinity of VO4 was calculated by taking the energy difference between the optimized geometry of neutral and anionic cluster). In methyl phenyl sulfide, there are lone pairs of electrons centered on a sulfur atom (Fig. 3(a)), its reaction with VO4 is likely to proceed by electrophilic attack of VO4 on sulfide with the donation of the lone electron pair of sulfide to the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) of VO4. As VO4 is an open shell system, its highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) is singly filled. The incoming electron from sulfide can either enter into the half filled HOMO, resulting into a singlet spin state (1VO4−) or the LUMO which will result in a triplet spin state (3VO4−). The incoming electron density is most likely to be accommodated in the half filled HOMO of VO4 as 1VO4− is more stable than 3VO4− by 21.38 kcal mol−1. As discussed above, the VO4 moiety has two types of linkages, oxo and peroxo; it is to be noted that the HOMO of VO4 is centered on the peroxo oxygen atoms (Fig. 3(b)), and the electron transfer from sulfide to VO4 weakens the peroxo linkage as the HOMO of VO4− is mainly the πg* orbital of the peroxo ligand (which is an antibonding orbital, Fig. 3(a)). This has also been confirmed by density functional calculations of Vyboishchikov and Sauer38 and Jia et al.63 Accordingly, out of the two possible sites i.e. (Operoxo and Ooxo), the weaker peroxo site of the VO4 moiety was found to be the sensitive site for the reaction.
From Soup: 8 The VO 4 moiety has a high electron affinity of 81.71 kcal mol −1 (the adiabatic electron affinity of VO 4 was calculated by taking the energy difference between the optimized geometry of neutral and anionic cluster). In methyl phenyl sulfide, there are lone pairs of electrons centered on a sulfur atom ( Fig. 3(a) ), its reaction with VO 4 is likely to proceed by electrophilic attack of VO 4 on sulfide with the donation of the lone electron pair of sulfide to the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) of VO 4 . As VO 4 is an open shell system, its highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) is singly filled. The incoming electron from sulfide can either enter into the half filled HOMO, resulting into a singlet spin state ( 1 VO 4 − ) or the LUMO which will result in a triplet spin state ( 3 VO 4 − ). The incoming electron density is most likely to be accommodated in the half filled HOMO of VO 4 as 1 VO 4 − is more stable than 3 VO 4 − by 21.38 kcal mol −1 . As discussed above, the VO 4 moiety has two types of linkages, oxo and peroxo; it is to be noted that the HOMO of VO 4 is centered on the peroxo oxygen atoms ( Fig. 3(b) ), and the electron transfer from sulfide to VO 4 weakens the peroxo linkage as the HOMO of VO 4 − is mainly the π g * orbital of the peroxo ligand (which is an antibonding orbital, Fig. 3(a) ). This has also been confirmed by density functional calculations of Vyboishchikov and Sauer 38 and Jia et al. 63 Accordingly, out of the two possible sites i.e. (O peroxo and O oxo ), the weaker peroxo site of the VO 4 moiety was found to be the sensitive site for the reaction.
 ###### 
From cou.: 9 Like trigonal carbon compounds, two ‘‘faces’’ or ‘‘sides’’ can be defined for a sulfide molecular plane; preferential reagent attack at one face generates stereoselectivity. The two faces are “enantiotopic” and attack at each face leads to enantiomers. Fig. 4 shows the two possible enantiotopic facial approaches of the electrophile (VO4) to the sulfide plane that lead to different enantiomeric products. The reaction is initiated by placing one of the enantiotopic faces of CH3-S-Ph in the vicinity of Operoxo(O4) of the VO4 moiety and coordinate drive calculations were carried out against the dihedral angle (V–O4peroxo–S–Ph) as a reaction coordinate for both the enantiotopic faces (Fig. 5). The scan was performed for 180° rotation with increment of 4° to scan all the possible orientations. The relaxed scans allowed for readjustment of the geometries of the reacting molecules at each step and helped us to guess the TS geometry. The two alternate options for an electrophile (VO4) to approach the sulfide plane (Fig. 4) lead to two different TSs (RTS and STS). The geometry corresponding to maxima in both the scans (Fig. 5) was subjected to optimization according to the Berny algorithm, and each one corresponded to one imaginary frequency of 35.05i cm−1 and 21.22i cm−1 respectively. The free energy profiles for both pathways (a and b in Fig. 4) at 298 K and 1 atm pressure for the reaction of VO4 are depicted in Fig. 6. It is to be noted that the reaction between VO4 and CH3-S-Ph involves a barrierless TS with respect to the reactants (R), which are infinitely separated. One of the oxygens (O4) of the peroxo linkage of VO4 forms a linkage with a sulfur atom, while the other (O3) binds strongly with vanadium to form a VO3 unit39 (geometries of stationary points with structural parameters are given in Fig. 6). The complex formed [VO3–O–S(CH3)(Ph)] has been stabilized with the release of energy. The occurrence of a barrierless TS indicates the vigorous reactivity of VO4 towards CH3-S-Ph at low/room temperature. It is interesting to note that a chiral centre has been generated at the sulfur atom; all four groups (methyl, phenyl, oxygen and a lone pair of electrons) attached to the sulfur are different but the reaction is not likely to be enantioselective as neither the reactants nor the catalyst is chiral. The inclusion of dispersion correction lowers the energy of all the stationary points. (Fig. 6(b)).
From Soup: 9 Like trigonal carbon compounds, two ‘‘faces’’ or ‘‘sides’’ can be defined for a sulfide molecular plane; preferential reagent attack at one face generates stereoselectivity. The two faces are “enantiotopic” and attack at each face leads to enantiomers. Fig. 4 shows the two possible enantiotopic facial approaches of the electrophile (VO 4 ) to the sulfide plane that lead to different enantiomeric products. The reaction is initiated by placing one of the enantiotopic faces of CH 3 -S-Ph in the vicinity of O peroxo (O 4 ) of the VO 4 moiety and coordinate drive calculations were carried out against the dihedral angle (V–O 4 peroxo –S–Ph) as a reaction coordinate for both the enantiotopic faces ( Fig. 5 ). The scan was performed for 180° rotation with increment of 4° to scan all the possible orientations. The relaxed scans allowed for readjustment of the geometries of the reacting molecules at each step and helped us to guess the TS geometry. The two alternate options for an electrophile (VO 4 ) to approach the sulfide plane ( Fig. 4 ) lead to two different TSs ( R TS and S TS). The geometry corresponding to maxima in both the scans ( Fig. 5 ) was subjected to optimization according to the Berny algorithm, and each one corresponded to one imaginary frequency of 35.05i cm −1 and 21.22i cm −1 respectively. The free energy profiles for both pathways (a and b in Fig. 4 ) at 298 K and 1 atm pressure for the reaction of VO 4 are depicted in Fig. 6 . It is to be noted that the reaction between VO 4 and CH 3 -S-Ph involves a barrierless TS with respect to the reactants ( R ), which are infinitely separated. One of the oxygens (O 4 ) of the peroxo linkage of VO 4 forms a linkage with a sulfur atom, while the other (O 3 ) binds strongly with vanadium to form a VO 3 unit 39 (geometries of stationary points with structural parameters are given in Fig. 6 ). The complex formed [VO 3 –O–S(CH 3 )(Ph)] has been stabilized with the release of energy. The occurrence of a barrierless TS indicates the vigorous reactivity of VO 4 towards CH 3 -S-Ph at low/room temperature. It is interesting to note that a chiral centre has been generated at the sulfur atom; all four groups (methyl, phenyl, oxygen and a lone pair of electrons) attached to the sulfur are different but the reaction is not likely to be enantioselective as neither the reactants nor the catalyst is chiral. The inclusion of dispersion correction lowers the energy of all the stationary points. ( Fig. 6(b) ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 10 The preferential formation of either the R or S sulfoxide is decided by the energy difference between their corresponding TSs. Though the two TSs have higher energy difference after optimization with dispersion correction, it is to be noted that in a gas phase reaction, the product formed at the end is a complex of VO4 and CH3-S-Ph. However, the reaction is facile and shows the promise of enantioselectivity as the addition of oxygen to the prochiral sulfide has generated a chiral centre at the sulfur atom.
From Soup: 10 The preferential formation of either the R or S sulfoxide is decided by the energy difference between their corresponding TSs. Though the two TSs have higher energy difference after optimization with dispersion correction, it is to be noted that in a gas phase reaction, the product formed at the end is a complex of VO 4 and CH 3 -S-Ph. However, the reaction is facile and shows the promise of enantioselectivity as the addition of oxygen to the prochiral sulfide has generated a chiral centre at the sulfur atom.
 ###### 
From cou.: 11 It is a known fact that enantioselectivity in organic synthesis is difficult to achieve as enantiomers possess identical enthalpies and entropies, and hence are produced in equal amounts by an undirected process – leading to a racemic mixture. The solution is to introduce a chiral feature which will promote the formation of one enantiomer over another via interactions at the transition state. This is known as asymmetric induction and can involve chiral features in the substrate, reagent, catalyst or environment.64 This works by lowering the activation energy required to form one enantiomer compared to that of the opposing enantiomer.65 In the present study, methyl phenyl sulfoxide produced as a result of the reaction between CH3-S-Ph and VO4 has a chiral centre but the stereoselectivity of the obtained product is low as none of the reactants has a chiral centre. The stereoselectivity in this reaction can be attained by introducing chirality in either the CH3-S-Ph or VO4 moiety. While no change was possible in the reactant CH3-S-Ph, we thought of modifying the structure of the VO4 moiety. In this context, it is pertinent to mention here that in the computational study reported by Balcells and coworkers66 enantioselectivity has been achieved by generating a chiral centre at vanadium such that two diastereomeric forms of the catalyst (V(O)(L)(OOH) where L = bulky tridentate Schiff base) could exist. It has been shown that each of these diastereomeric forms of the catalyst can further result in either the R or S enantiomer of the sulfoxide product. Motivated by the above approach and high reactivity of VO4 towards CH3-S-Ph, it was worthwhile to modify the structure of the VO4 moiety. While in the reported study,66 chirality in the vanadium complex has been introduced by changing the ligand, the present approach is to adsorb the VO4 on a substrate to generate a chiral centre. The current approach is novel and has direct experimental relevance as in contrast to the gas phase computational studies reported in the literature, the experimental studies are feasible only either in solvent or on a solid support.5–7,19
From Soup: 11 It is a known fact that enantioselectivity in organic synthesis is difficult to achieve as enantiomers possess identical enthalpies and entropies, and hence are produced in equal amounts by an undirected process – leading to a racemic mixture. The solution is to introduce a chiral feature which will promote the formation of one enantiomer over another via interactions at the transition state. This is known as asymmetric induction and can involve chiral features in the substrate, reagent, catalyst or environment. 64 This works by lowering the activation energy required to form one enantiomer compared to that of the opposing enantiomer. 65 In the present study, methyl phenyl sulfoxide produced as a result of the reaction between CH 3 -S-Ph and VO 4 has a chiral centre but the stereoselectivity of the obtained product is low as none of the reactants has a chiral centre. The stereoselectivity in this reaction can be attained by introducing chirality in either the CH 3 -S-Ph or VO 4 moiety. While no change was possible in the reactant CH 3 -S-Ph, we thought of modifying the structure of the VO 4 moiety. In this context, it is pertinent to mention here that in the computational study reported by Balcells and coworkers 66 enantioselectivity has been achieved by generating a chiral centre at vanadium such that two diastereomeric forms of the catalyst (V(O)(L)(OOH) where L = bulky tridentate Schiff base) could exist. It has been shown that each of these diastereomeric forms of the catalyst can further result in either the R or S enantiomer of the sulfoxide product. Motivated by the above approach and high reactivity of VO 4 towards CH 3 -S-Ph, it was worthwhile to modify the structure of the VO 4 moiety. While in the reported study, 66 chirality in the vanadium complex has been introduced by changing the ligand, the present approach is to adsorb the VO 4 on a substrate to generate a chiral centre. The current approach is novel and has direct experimental relevance as in contrast to the gas phase computational studies reported in the literature, the experimental studies are feasible only either in solvent or on a solid support. 5–7,19
 ###### 
From cou.: 12 It is well documented that a local environment inside the mesopores of the support affects the enantioselectivity of the reaction.67–69 Therefore, it is prudent to graft the metal complex on a suitable solid support. Ordered mesoporous solids like MCM-41 and SBA-15, are potential materials for heterogenization of a valuable homogeneous catalyst. It is to be emphasized that enhanced catalytic activity of a transition metal on the mesoporous support has been established by various experimental studies.45,46,70 Recently a new system has been designed that uses hydrogen peroxide at room temperature in the presence of zirconium oxide complex-functionalized mesoporous MCM-41 (Zr-oxide@MCM-41) as a catalyst for the oxidation of sulfides into sulfoxides as well as for oxidative coupling of thiols into their corresponding disulfides.46 Bearing this in mind, we optimized the SBA-15 silica support (Fig. 7). In order to graft the metal complex on the SBA-15 support, the VO4 moiety was placed both near the edges (site (A) Fig. 7) and in the centre of SBA-15 (site (B) in Fig. 7). The VO4 moiety gets adsorbed at the centre of SBA-15 with the liberation of 57 kcal mol−1 of energy but the adsorption energy (Eadsorption = ESBA-15-VO4 − (ESBA-15 + EVO4)) was found to be positive for adsorption at the edge of the SBA-15 surface. The adsorption energy has also been calculated from the full QM calculations using dispersion correction, and the SPE of the ONIOM optimized geometries of VO4 grafted at the centre of SBA-15 was found to be 68.34 kcal mol−1. The lowering of the adsorption energy after taking into consideration the dispersion correction suggests that long range forces are important for the interactions between VO4 and the SBA-15 support.
From Soup: 12 It is well documented that a local environment inside the mesopores of the support affects the enantioselectivity of the reaction. 67–69 Therefore, it is prudent to graft the metal complex on a suitable solid support. Ordered mesoporous solids like MCM-41 and SBA-15, are potential materials for heterogenization of a valuable homogeneous catalyst. It is to be emphasized that enhanced catalytic activity of a transition metal on the mesoporous support has been established by various experimental studies. 45,46,70 Recently a new system has been designed that uses hydrogen peroxide at room temperature in the presence of zirconium oxide complex-functionalized mesoporous MCM-41 (Zr-oxide@MCM-41) as a catalyst for the oxidation of sulfides into sulfoxides as well as for oxidative coupling of thiols into their corresponding disulfides. 46 Bearing this in mind, we optimized the SBA-15 silica support ( Fig. 7 ). In order to graft the metal complex on the SBA-15 support, the VO 4 moiety was placed both near the edges (site (A) Fig. 7 ) and in the centre of SBA-15 (site (B) in Fig. 7 ). The VO 4 moiety gets adsorbed at the centre of SBA-15 with the liberation of 57 kcal mol −1 of energy but the adsorption energy ( E adsorption = E SBA-15-VO 4 − ( E SBA-15 + E VO 4 )) was found to be positive for adsorption at the edge of the SBA-15 surface. The adsorption energy has also been calculated from the full QM calculations using dispersion correction, and the SPE of the ONIOM optimized geometries of VO 4 grafted at the centre of SBA-15 was found to be 68.34 kcal mol −1 . The lowering of the adsorption energy after taking into consideration the dispersion correction suggests that long range forces are important for the interactions between VO 4 and the SBA-15 support.
