From cou.: 14 The chirality of the vanadium atom in the stereoselective catalyst and two enantiotopic faces of sulfide will influence the stability of TSs which further controls the selectivity of the product. The reaction of the SBA-15 embedded chiral RVO4 moiety with two enantiotopic faces of sulfide (Fig. 4) leads to two TSs; the corresponding energy profile is depicted in Fig. 9. DFT optimized geometries of en route TSs are shown in Fig. 10. Both the TSs (RTS and STS) had one imaginary frequency of 711i cm−1 and 748i cm−1 respectively. Their connectivity to the corresponding reactants and products has been confirmed by IRC calculations. The transfer of electron density from sulfide to the VO4 moiety is evident from the increase of nearly 0.65e partial positive charge on the sulfur atom and increase of partial negative charge on oxygen atoms of the VO4 moiety (Table 1). The transfer of electron density from the sulfur atom of sulfide to periodates has also been observed in the study of Ruff et al.71 The MEP plots of both the TSs (Fig. 11) provide concrete evidence of the shift of electron density from sulfide to the VO4 moiety. It is noticeable that in the case of RTS, the transfer of electron density is more (Fig. 11a) than in the case of STS wherein the electron density is delocalized between both the reactants (Fig. 11b). Enantioselectivity has been traditionally quantified by evaluating the enantiomeric excess according to the equations below:60
From Soup: 14 The chirality of the vanadium atom in the stereoselective catalyst and two enantiotopic faces of sulfide will influence the stability of TSs which further controls the selectivity of the product. The reaction of the SBA-15 embedded chiral R VO 4 moiety with two enantiotopic faces of sulfide ( Fig. 4 ) leads to two TSs; the corresponding energy profile is depicted in Fig. 9 . DFT optimized geometries of en route TSs are shown in Fig. 10 . Both the TSs ( R TS and S TS) had one imaginary frequency of 711i cm −1 and 748i cm −1 respectively. Their connectivity to the corresponding reactants and products has been confirmed by IRC calculations. The transfer of electron density from sulfide to the VO 4 moiety is evident from the increase of nearly 0.65 e partial positive charge on the sulfur atom and increase of partial negative charge on oxygen atoms of the VO 4 moiety ( Table 1 ). The transfer of electron density from the sulfur atom of sulfide to periodates has also been observed in the study of Ruff et al. 71 The MEP plots of both the TSs ( Fig. 11 ) provide concrete evidence of the shift of electron density from sulfide to the VO 4 moiety. It is noticeable that in the case of R TS, the transfer of electron density is more ( Fig. 11a ) than in the case of S TS wherein the electron density is delocalized between both the reactants ( Fig. 11b ). Enantioselectivity has been traditionally quantified by evaluating the enantiomeric excess according to the equations below: 60
