From cou.: 24 The free energy difference between RTS and STS is 16.72 kcal mol−1, and the enantiomeric excess (%ee) calculated using this difference (eqn (4)) is 100%. This indicates preferential formation of the R enantiomer of sulfoxide.
From Soup: 24 In the gas phase, the sulfoxidation of CH 3 -S-Ph by VO 4 was found to be a barrierless process while with SBA-15 supported VO 4 the reaction proceeds through a barrier of 50.56 kcal mol −1 . This may be attributed to the increase in coordination of VO 4 when supported on the SBA-15 that imparts it extra stability. The increase in activation barrier for the supported cluster vis-à-vis the unsupported moiety is reported in the literature. 72,73
 ###### 
From cou.: 25 In the gas phase, the sulfoxidation of CH3-S-Ph by VO4 was found to be a barrierless process while with SBA-15 supported VO4 the reaction proceeds through a barrier of 50.56 kcal mol−1. This may be attributed to the increase in coordination of VO4 when supported on the SBA-15 that imparts it extra stability. The increase in activation barrier for the supported cluster vis-à-vis the unsupported moiety is reported in the literature.72,73
From Soup: 25 Both the TSs led to the respective R and S products with sp 3 centre chirality at sulfur with one lone pair of electrons (Fig. S1 in the ESI † ). The sulfoxide formed in the reaction has a pyramidal geometry as the angle is distorted from a normal tetrahedral angle of 108° (<O–S–Ph = 105.7°).
 ###### 
From cou.: 26 Both the TSs led to the respective R and S products with sp3 centre chirality at sulfur with one lone pair of electrons (Fig. S1 in the ESI†). The sulfoxide formed in the reaction has a pyramidal geometry as the angle is distorted from a normal tetrahedral angle of 108° (<O–S–Ph = 105.7°).
From Soup: 26 To persuade a chiral catalyst to transfer the chiral information stored in its structure to the reactant via interaction at the transition state, both steric and electronic effects play a significant role, and it is well accepted that nature uses both these effects to promote chiral recognition. 74–79 Rationalization of the origin of the differential stabilization in stereo controlling the TSs is carried out by using activation strain analysis. The contribution of strain and interaction energy in the activation energy has been computed. 80 In an activation strain model, activation energies Δ E a are decomposed into the activation strain Δ E strain of the reactants and the interaction energy Δ E int between the reactants in the activated complex: Δ E a = Δ E strain + Δ E int . The activation strain Δ E strain depends on the strength of the activated bond and on the extent to which a particular metal–oxygen bond expands in the activated complex. The interaction energy Δ E int is directly determined by the bonding capabilities of the reactants. 81 In this case the destabilizing strain energy of both the R and S TSs is the same (64.55 kcal mol −1 ) whereas the stabilizing interaction energy of R TS (−35.25 kcal mol −1 ) is higher than that of S TS (−16.19 kcal mol −1 ) ( Table 2 ). This suggests that the energy difference between the R and S TSs that leads to enantioselectivity is owing to more favorable interactions between the reacting species in the R orientation than in the S orientation.
 ###### 
From cou.: 27 To persuade a chiral catalyst to transfer the chiral information stored in its structure to the reactant via interaction at the transition state, both steric and electronic effects play a significant role, and it is well accepted that nature uses both these effects to promote chiral recognition.74–79 Rationalization of the origin of the differential stabilization in stereo controlling the TSs is carried out by using activation strain analysis. The contribution of strain and interaction energy in the activation energy has been computed.80 In an activation strain model, activation energies ΔEa are decomposed into the activation strain ΔEstrain of the reactants and the interaction energy ΔEint between the reactants in the activated complex: ΔEa = ΔEstrain + ΔEint. The activation strain ΔEstrain depends on the strength of the activated bond and on the extent to which a particular metal–oxygen bond expands in the activated complex. The interaction energy ΔEint is directly determined by the bonding capabilities of the reactants.81 In this case the destabilizing strain energy of both the R and S TSs is the same (64.55 kcal mol−1) whereas the stabilizing interaction energy of RTS (−35.25 kcal mol−1) is higher than that of STS (−16.19 kcal mol−1) (Table 2). This suggests that the energy difference between the R and S TSs that leads to enantioselectivity is owing to more favorable interactions between the reacting species in the R orientation than in the S orientation.
From Soup: 27 Careful analysis of the structure of both TSs ( Fig. 10 ) shows that orientation of the phenyl ring with respect to the SBA-15 support is markedly different in R TS and S TS, and the orientation of the phenyl ring in R TS ( Fig. 10(a) ) facilitates its π-interaction with SBA-15. In order to probe the role of π-interaction between the phenyl ring and SBA-15, we investigated a similar reaction by replacing an aryl group with ethyl (CH 3 -S-C 2 H 5 ). Interestingly, the free energy profile for the reaction of CH 3 -S-C 2 H 5 with VO 4 -SBA-15 ( Fig. 12 ) indicates that the enantiomeric excess is only 62% corresponding to an energy difference of 0.86 kcal mol −1 between R TS and S TS. This leads us to important conclusions that while an SBA-15 embedded VO 4 moiety introduces enantioselectivity to the sulfoxide, the role of substituent groups attached to the sulfur atom in the sulfide is crucial for obtaining large enantiomeric excess. This is in agreement with the experimental report of Kagan and Rebiere. 82
 ###### 
From cou.: 28 Careful analysis of the structure of both TSs (Fig. 10) shows that orientation of the phenyl ring with respect to the SBA-15 support is markedly different in RTS and STS, and the orientation of the phenyl ring in RTS (Fig. 10(a)) facilitates its π-interaction with SBA-15. In order to probe the role of π-interaction between the phenyl ring and SBA-15, we investigated a similar reaction by replacing an aryl group with ethyl (CH3-S-C2H5). Interestingly, the free energy profile for the reaction of CH3-S-C2H5 with VO4-SBA-15 (Fig. 12) indicates that the enantiomeric excess is only 62% corresponding to an energy difference of 0.86 kcal mol−1 between RTS and STS. This leads us to important conclusions that while an SBA-15 embedded VO4 moiety introduces enantioselectivity to the sulfoxide, the role of substituent groups attached to the sulfur atom in the sulfide is crucial for obtaining large enantiomeric excess. This is in agreement with the experimental report of Kagan and Rebiere.82
From Soup: 28 It was observed that both the R and S enantiomers of SBA-15 embedded VO 4 had nearly the same energy. While, as discussed above the R enantiomer led to large enantiomeric excess, we further investigated the reaction of the S isomer ( S VO 4 -SBA-15) with sulfide. As in the previous case, the reaction was carried out with both the enantiotopic faces of sulfide ( Fig. 4 ) and the corresponding TSs are ( R TS and S TS) shown in Fig. 13 . The energy profile indicates high enantiomeric excess (100% according to eqn (4) ) for the energy difference of 9.18 kcal mol −1 between the two TSs (see Fig. S2 for optimized geometries of the TSs, ESI † ). The reaction was selective towards the S enantiomer of sulfoxide, which lies lower in energy, wherein, the phenyl ring is oriented towards SBA-15 (Fig. S2 in the ESI † ). The activation strain analysis ( Table 2 ), NBO analysis (Table S1 in the ESI † ) and MEP surfaces (Fig. S3 in the ESI † ) are suggestive of a larger shift in electron density in the case of S TS. The orientation of the phenyl ring in more stabilized TSs suggests that the combination of electronic and steric effects provides enantioselectivity to the reaction. The electronic interactions in the transition state are mainly characterized by donation of electron density from the sulfur atom of sulfide to the vanadium-peroxo fragment. The sulfide acts as a nucleophile in this oxidation reaction, which agrees with the experimental observation that sulfide is the nucleophile in an oxidation reaction with vanadium-peroxo complexes. 83
 ###### 
From cou.: 29 It was observed that both the R and S enantiomers of SBA-15 embedded VO4 had nearly the same energy. While, as discussed above the R enantiomer led to large enantiomeric excess, we further investigated the reaction of the S isomer (SVO4-SBA-15) with sulfide. As in the previous case, the reaction was carried out with both the enantiotopic faces of sulfide (Fig. 4) and the corresponding TSs are (RTS and STS) shown in Fig. 13. The energy profile indicates high enantiomeric excess (100% according to eqn (4)) for the energy difference of 9.18 kcal mol−1 between the two TSs (see Fig. S2 for optimized geometries of the TSs, ESI†). The reaction was selective towards the S enantiomer of sulfoxide, which lies lower in energy, wherein, the phenyl ring is oriented towards SBA-15 (Fig. S2 in the ESI†). The activation strain analysis (Table 2), NBO analysis (Table S1 in the ESI†) and MEP surfaces (Fig. S3 in the ESI†) are suggestive of a larger shift in electron density in the case of STS. The orientation of the phenyl ring in more stabilized TSs suggests that the combination of electronic and steric effects provides enantioselectivity to the reaction. The electronic interactions in the transition state are mainly characterized by donation of electron density from the sulfur atom of sulfide to the vanadium-peroxo fragment. The sulfide acts as a nucleophile in this oxidation reaction, which agrees with the experimental observation that sulfide is the nucleophile in an oxidation reaction with vanadium-peroxo complexes.83
From Soup: 29 It is to be noted that in the case of sp 3 centered chirality, when the stereocentre has a lone pair of electrons, both enantiomers can interconvert through a process called pyramidal inversion in which a mirror image is formed through a trigonal planar TS. 84 We obtained the trigonal planar TS ( Fig. 14 ) in the pathway of inter-conversion of two enantiomers, R and S of methyl phenyl sulfoxide that was confirmed by IRC calculations. It has been well documented in the literature that the inversion barrier of 29 kcal mol −1 observed in the present case is sufficiently high for preferential synthesis of one enantiomer. 85
 ###### 
From cou.: 30 It is to be noted that in the case of sp3 centered chirality, when the stereocentre has a lone pair of electrons, both enantiomers can interconvert through a process called pyramidal inversion in which a mirror image is formed through a trigonal planar TS.84 We obtained the trigonal planar TS (Fig. 14) in the pathway of inter-conversion of two enantiomers, R and S of methyl phenyl sulfoxide that was confirmed by IRC calculations. It has been well documented in the literature that the inversion barrier of 29 kcal mol−1 observed in the present case is sufficiently high for preferential synthesis of one enantiomer.85
From Soup: 30 In most experimental studies H 2 O 2 is used as an oxidant for the sulfoxidation reactions. The regeneration of the catalyst (VO 4 ) is investigated using H 2 O 2 as an oxidant. Fig. 15 shows the DFT calculated reaction profile for the reaction of VO 3 with H 2 O 2 . Firstly, H 2 O 2 forms a complex with VO 3 which is stabilized by 18.59 kcal mol −1 and is further converted into a product (VO 4 + H 2 O) via TS with the liberation of 48.48 kcal mol −1 of energy.
 ###### 
From cou.: 31 In most experimental studies H2O2 is used as an oxidant for the sulfoxidation reactions. The regeneration of the catalyst (VO4) is investigated using H2O2 as an oxidant. Fig. 15 shows the DFT calculated reaction profile for the reaction of VO3 with H2O2. Firstly, H2O2 forms a complex with VO3 which is stabilized by 18.59 kcal mol−1 and is further converted into a product (VO4 + H2O) via TS with the liberation of 48.48 kcal mol−1 of energy.
From Soup: 31 The computational study presented here not only elaborates the mechanism of asymmetric oxidation of prochiral sulfide by VO 4 , but also proposes a suitable method to introduce enantioselectivity in the reaction. The heterogenization of the VO 4 moiety on the SBA-15 makes it chiral, the reactivity of each enantiomer of SBA-15 embedded VO 4 with prochiral sulfide is investigated through exhaustive computations performed within the formalism of DFT. The R enantiomer of SBA-15 embedded VO 4 leads to preferential formation of the R sulfoxide while the S enantiomer leads to the S sulfoxide. The % ee calculated in both cases from the free energy difference between the corresponding TSs is nearly 100%. Furthermore, the observed barrier for interconversion of the R and S enantiomer of sulfoxide through pyramidal inversion is sufficiently large for selective formation of one enantiomer.
 ###### 
From cou.: 32 The computational study presented here not only elaborates the mechanism of asymmetric oxidation of prochiral sulfide by VO4, but also proposes a suitable method to introduce enantioselectivity in the reaction. The heterogenization of the VO4 moiety on the SBA-15 makes it chiral, the reactivity of each enantiomer of SBA-15 embedded VO4 with prochiral sulfide is investigated through exhaustive computations performed within the formalism of DFT. The R enantiomer of SBA-15 embedded VO4 leads to preferential formation of the R sulfoxide while the S enantiomer leads to the S sulfoxide. The % ee calculated in both cases from the free energy difference between the corresponding TSs is nearly 100%. Furthermore, the observed barrier for interconversion of the R and S enantiomer of sulfoxide through pyramidal inversion is sufficiently large for selective formation of one enantiomer.
From Soup: 32 The results presented here are of relevance in experimental synthesis of chiral sulfoxides as there are numerous instances of the use of vanadium oxide clusters and the SBA-15 mesoporous support in practical applications. Grafting the cluster on SBA-15 to produce large enantiomeric excess of sulfoxide is a novel approach and the study offers a rational explanation of the crucial role of electronic and steric factors and provides useful pointers to experimentalists for the chiral synthesis of sulfoxides that have high industrial/pharmaceutical importance.
 ###### 
